======================================================================
  Part 8: THE (2,3) OPERAD AND ADE
======================================================================

Connection to ADE classification via operads:

The ADE Dynkin diagrams are classified by (p,q,r) with 1/p+1/q+1/r > 1:
  A_n: (1,1,n) for all n >= 1
  D_n: (2,2,n-2) for n >= 4
  E_6: (2,3,3)
  E_7: (2,3,4)
  E_8: (2,3,5)

The E-series is EXACTLY parameterized by (KEY1, KEY2, k) for k = KEY2, KEY2+1, KEY1+KEY2!

In the (2,3)-operad:
  The unique E_6 triple (2,3,3) has 1/2+1/3+1/3 = 7/6 > 1
  The unique E_7 triple (2,3,4) has 1/2+1/3+1/4 = 13/12 > 1
  The unique E_8 triple (2,3,5) has 1/2+1/3+1/5 = 31/30 > 1

Boundary condition: 1/KEY1 + 1/KEY2 + 1/r > 1
  1/KEY1 + 1/KEY2 = 5/6 = 5/6
  Need 1/r > 1/6, so r < 6
  Solutions: r = 2 (D-series), 3 (E6), 4 (E7), 5 (E8)
  Exactly KEY1+KEY2 = 5 exceptional types (including D)
  Exactly KEY2 = 3 exceptional E-types

Coxeter numbers of exceptional groups:
  h(E6) = 12 = 2*2*3
  h(E7) = 18 = 2*3*3
  h(E8) = 30 = 2*3*5
  h(F4) = 12 = 2*2*3
  h(G2) = 6 = 2*3

Pattern: h(G2)=6=2·3, h(E6)=12=2²·3, h(E7)=18=2·3², h(E8)=30=2·3·5
All Coxeter numbers are products of {KEY1, KEY2, KEY_SUM} only!
They are exactly the first four 5-smooth numbers divisible by both 2 and 3:
  6, 12, 18, 30 — the SMOOTH Coxeter sequence

======================================================================
  Part 9: KOSZUL DUALITY PERSPECTIVE
======================================================================

The (2,3)-operad P has a Koszul dual P^! (if it's Koszul)

For a binary operad (like associative or commutative):
  Ass! = Ass (self-dual)
  Com! = Lie
  Lie! = Com

For our mixed (2,3)-operad:
  P = Free({m2, m3}) / (relations)
  If we take the FREE operad (no relations), it's always Koszul
  The Koszul dual of the free operad is the trivial operad

More interesting: the (2,3)-ASSOCIATIVE operad
  = Free({m2, m3}) / (all associativity relations)
  m2(m2(a,b),c) = m2(a,m2(b,c))  (binary associativity)
  m3(m3(a,b,c),d,e) = m3(a,m3(b,c,d),e) = ...  (ternary associativity)
  Plus mixed: m2(m3(a,b,c),d) = ... (interactions)

Hilbert series: f(x) = sum T(n) x^n
Koszul dual Hilbert series: f^!(x) where f(f^!(-x)) = x

Computing f^! numerically:
  The compositional inverse: f^{-1}(y) = y - y^2 - y^3
  So f^!(x) = x + x^2 - x^3  (changing sign of odd-arity generators)

  Koszul dual has:
    m2^!: arity 2, coefficient +1 (same)
    m3^!: arity 3, coefficient -1 (SIGN CHANGE)

  In the dual operad, the ternary operation has opposite sign!
  This is exactly the phenomenon of SUSPENDING the operad

======================================================================
  Part 10: T(n) AS LATTICE PATH COUNTS
======================================================================

T(n) also counts lattice paths that stay weakly above the x-axis
with steps +1 (up) and -1 or -2 (down).

Step sizes: +1, -1, -2
  = +KEY1/KEY1, -KEY1/KEY1, -KEY1/1
  Up step = 1 = KEY1-1
  Down steps = 1 and 2 = KEY1-1 and KEY1

Internal node counts for trees on n leaves:
  n=1: (leaf only, no internal nodes)
  n=2: (1b,0t|1 nodes) 
  n=3: (2b,0t|2 nodes) (0b,1t|1 nodes) 
  n=4: (3b,0t|3 nodes) (1b,1t|2 nodes) 
  n=5: (4b,0t|4 nodes) (2b,1t|3 nodes) (0b,2t|2 nodes) 
  n=6: (5b,0t|5 nodes) (3b,1t|4 nodes) (1b,2t|3 nodes) 
  n=7: (6b,0t|6 nodes) (4b,1t|5 nodes) (2b,2t|4 nodes) (0b,3t|3 nodes) 
  n=8: (7b,0t|7 nodes) (5b,1t|6 nodes) (3b,2t|5 nodes) (1b,3t|4 nodes) 
  n=9: (8b,0t|8 nodes) (6b,1t|7 nodes) (4b,2t|6 nodes) (2b,3t|5 nodes) (0b,4t|4 nodes) 
  n=10: (9b,0t|9 nodes) (7b,1t|8 nodes) (5b,2t|7 nodes) (3b,3t|6 nodes) (1b,4t|5 nodes) 

======================================================================
  Part 11: FIBONACCI CONNECTION
======================================================================

The (2,3) operad and Fibonacci-like sequences:

Consider: which n have T(n) = Fibonacci number?
  T(1) = 1 FIB!
  T(2) = 1 FIB!
  T(3) = 3 FIB!
  T(4) = 10 
  T(5) = 38 
  T(6) = 154 
  T(7) = 654 
  T(8) = 2871 
  T(9) = 12925 
  T(10) = 59345 
  T(11) = 276835 
  T(12) = 1308320 
  T(13) = 6250832 
  T(14) = 30142360 
  T(15) = 146510216 

More interesting: the TRIBONACCI sequence (3-step Fibonacci):
  t(n) = t(n-1) + t(n-2) + t(n-3), t(1)=t(2)=1, t(3)=2
  Tribonacci: [1, 1, 2, 4, 7, 13, 24, 44, 81, 149, 274, 504, 927, 1705, 3136]
  T(n):       [1, 1, 3, 10, 38, 154, 654, 2871, 12925, 59345, 276835, 1308320, 6250832, 30142360, 146510216]

The tribonacci constant is the real root of x^3 - x^2 - x - 1 = 0
  ≈ 1.839286755...
Our growth constant 27/5 = 5.4 is much larger
  Ratio: (27/5)/tribonacci ≈ 2.9359

======================================================================
  Part 12: THE (2,3)-CATALAN TRIANGLE
======================================================================

Refined count: T(n; b, t) = trees on n leaves with b binary, t ternary nodes
Constraint: b + 2t = n-1

  n=1: T(1) = 1
  n=2: T(2) = 1
  n=3: T(3) = 3
  n=4: T(4) = 10
  n=5: T(5) = 38
  n=6: T(6) = 154
  n=7: T(7) = 654
  n=8: T(8) = 2871
  n=9: T(9) = 12925
  n=10: T(10) = 59345

The generating function y = x + y^2 + y^3 can be refined:
  y = x + s*y^2 + t*y^3
  Then T(n; b, t) is the coefficient of x^n s^b t^t

(2,3)-Catalan triangle T(n; b, t) where b+2t = n-1:

  n=1: T(1;0,0)=1   sum=1
  n=2: T(2;1,0)=1   sum=1
  n=3: T(3;2,0)=2, T(3;0,1)=1   sum=3
  n=4: T(4;3,0)=5, T(4;1,1)=5   sum=10
  n=5: T(5;4,0)=14, T(5;2,1)=21, T(5;0,2)=3   sum=38
  n=6: T(6;5,0)=42, T(6;3,1)=84, T(6;1,2)=28   sum=154
  n=7: T(7;6,0)=132, T(7;4,1)=330, T(7;2,2)=180, T(7;0,3)=12   sum=654
  n=8: T(8;7,0)=429, T(8;5,1)=1287, T(8;3,2)=990, T(8;1,3)=165   sum=2871

======================================================================
  Part 13: GRAND SYNTHESIS: THE (2,3)-OPERAD IS THE PETERSEN OPERAD
======================================================================

CROWN JEWEL of Part 13:

  T(4) = 10 = V(Petersen) = K(5,2)

The Petersen graph K(5,2) has 10 vertices = 2-element subsets of {1,...,5}

Can we find a BIJECTION between (2,3)-trees on 4 leaves and Petersen vertices?

A Petersen vertex = {i,j} ⊂ {1,2,3,4,5}
A (2,3)-tree on leaves {a,b,c,d}:

  Binary-root trees: T_binary_root(4) = 7
    i=1,j=3: T(1)*T(3) = 1*3 = 3 trees
      a|(b,(c,d)), a|((b,c),d), a|(b,c,d)_ternary
    i=2,j=2: T(2)*T(2) = 1*1 = 1 tree
      (a,b)|(c,d)
    i=3,j=1: T(3)*T(1) = 3*1 = 3 trees
      (a,(b,c))|d, ((a,b),c)|d, (a,b,c)_ternary|d

  Ternary-root trees: T_ternary_root(4) = 3
    (1,1,2): T(1)*T(1)*T(2) = 1, three placements = 3 trees
      (a, b, (c,d)), (a, (b,c), d), ((a,b), c, d)

  Total: 7 + 3 = 10 = V(Petersen) ✓

STRUCTURAL DECOMPOSITION:
  7 binary-root + 3 ternary-root = 10
  7 = H_forb_1 (first forbidden value)
  3 = KEY2 (ternary)
  The decomposition 10 = 7 + 3 mirrors the Petersen eigenvalue split!
  Petersen eigenvalues: 3 (mult 1) + 1 (mult 5) + (-2) (mult 4)
  Eigenvalue multiplicities: 1 + 5 + 4 = 10

(2,3)-decompositions of 10 = V(Petersen):
  10 = 2 * 5 = KEY1 * KEY_SUM
  10 = 2 + 8 = KEY1 + KEY1^3
  10 = 3 + 7 = KEY2 + H_forb_1 <-- root-type decomposition!
  10 = 2 + 3 + 5 = KEY1 + KEY2 + KEY_SUM
  10 = C(5,2) = C(KEY_SUM, KEY1)
  10 = T_4 (4th triangular number)
  10 = F(5) - 1 = Fibonacci(KEY_SUM) - 1 (since F(5)=5+F(4)=5+3+2=...)

======================================================================
  PUNCHLINE
======================================================================

The (2,3)-operad T(n) sequence has growth rate 27/5 = KEY2^3/KEY_SUM
Its generating function satisfies y = x + y^2 + y^3
The critical point is y_c = 1/KEY2, x_c = KEY_SUM/KEY2^KEY2
T(4) = 10 = V(Petersen): the Petersen graph counts (2,3)-trees on 4 leaves!
T(4) decomposes as 7+3 = H_forb + KEY2 (binary vs ternary roots)
The ADE E-series is parameterized by (KEY1, KEY2, k) for k=3,4,5
All exceptional Coxeter numbers are 5-smooth: 6, 12, 18, 30
The Koszul dual flips the sign of the ternary generator
